# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: first-baseman
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:first-baseman/ace-baseball] In baseball, an **ace** is a starting pitcher considered the best pitcher on a team's starting rotation.
[src:first-baseman/ace-baseball] Barring injury or exceptional circumstances, a team's ace typically starts on Opening Day.
[src:first-baseman/ace-baseball] In addition, aces are usually preferred to start crucial playoff games, sometimes on three days' rest.
[src:first-baseman/ace-baseball] The term may be a derivation of the nickname of Asa Brainard (real first name: "Asahel"), a 19th-century star pitcher, who was sometimes referred to as "Ace".
[src:first-baseman/ace-baseball] In the early days of baseball, the term *ace* was used to refer to a run.
[src:first-baseman/ace-baseball] Modern baseball analysts and fans have started using the term *ace* to refer to the elite pitchers in the game, not necessarily to the best starting pitcher on each team.
[src:first-baseman/ace-baseball] For example, the April 27, 1981, *Sports Illustrated* cover was captioned "The Amazing A's and Their Five Aces" to describe the starting rotation of the 1981 Oakland Athletics, which featured Mike Norris, Rick Langford, Matt Keough, Steve McCatty, and Brian Kingman.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Near the end of his career, Kaline also played as first baseman and, in his last season, was the Tigers' designated hitter.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] He retired soon after reaching the 3,000 hit milestone late in the 1974 season.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Immediately after retiring from playing, he became the Tigers' TV color commentator, a position he held from 1975 until 2002.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Kaline worked for the Tigers as a front office assistant from 2003 until his death in 2020.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Kaline was born and raised in Baltimore, Maryland, the son of Naomi (Morgan) and Nicholas Kaline.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Several of his relatives played semi-professional baseball, but no one in the family had graduated from high school.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] When he was eight years old, Kaline developed osteomyelitis and had two inches of bone removed from his left foot.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] The surgery left him with scarring and permanent deformity, but he was an outstanding pitcher in youth baseball.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Kaline had learned to throw a fastball, changeup and curveball by the age of nine.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Kaline attended Baltimore's Southern High School, where he starred in basketball and also played football until he sustained a cheek injury.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] When he tried out for the baseball team, there was no room on the pitching staff so Kaline moved to the outfield.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] He earned all-state honors in baseball all four years.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Kaline said that he was a poor student but that he was well-liked by his teachers.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] He said that his teachers passed him, believing he would become a baseball player.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] At the time of Kaline's signing, the bonus rule implemented by Major League Baseball was still in effect.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] The rule stipulated that when a major league team signed a player to a contract with a signing bonus in excess of $4,000 ($58,000 today), the team was required to keep that player on their 25-man active roster for two full seasons.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] If the team failed to comply with the rule, they would lose the rights to that player's contract, and the player would then be exposed to the waiver wire.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] As Kaline had received a bonus of $15,000 ($216,000 today), he bypassed the minor leagues and joined the Tigers directly from high school.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] He made his major league debut on June 25, 1953 in Philadelphia as a late-inning replacement for outfielder Jim Delsing.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Kaline wore number 25 during his rookie campaign, but asked teammate Pat Mullin for his No.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] 6 when he retired after the 1953 season ended.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Kaline wore the number for the rest of his major league playing career.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] In 1955, at age 20, Kaline ended the season with a .340 batting average, becoming the youngest player ever to win the American League (AL) batting title.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] No 20-year-old major league player had won a batting title since Ty Cobb in 1907.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] During the 1955 season, Kaline became the 13th man in major league history to hit two home runs in the same inning, became the youngest to hit three home runs in one game, and finished the year with 200 hits, 27 home runs and 102 runs batted in (RBIs).
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] His 200 hits led the major leagues, and he also led the American League with 321 total bases.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Kaline finished second to Yogi Berra in the American League's 1955 Most Valuable Player Award voting.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] He was selected to the Major League Baseball All-Star Game, the first in a string of consecutive All-Star selections that lasted through 1967.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Kaline followed in 1956 with a .314 batting average, 27 home runs and a career-high 128 RBIs, finishing third in the AL MVP voting.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] He led the league in outfield assists with 18 in 1956 and again in 1958 with 23.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] In 1957, he won the first of what would be ten Gold Glove Awards over the next eleven seasons.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Kaline was out for several games in 1958 after he was hit by a pitch.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] He missed several games in 1959 after he was hit by a thrown ball and sustained a fracture in his cheekbone.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Kaline had been knocked out from the blow and initial speculation was that he could miss six weeks of the season.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Kaline ended up missing only 18 games, and finished the 1959 season with a .327 batting average and 27 home runs.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] He also led the AL in slugging percentage (.530) and OPS (.940).
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] By the time of his 26th birthday, Kaline had accumulated 1,200 hits, the third highest total by a 25-year-old player in MLB history, behind only Ty Cobb (1,433) and Mel Ott (1,249).
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Following the departure of Harvey Kuenn, Kaline played the entire 1960 season in center field, the only time of his career he would do so.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] In 1961, the Tigers acquired Bill Bruton from the Milwaukee Braves to play center field, allowing Kaline to move back to right field.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] In 1961, Kaline led the majors with 41 doubles and hit .324 to finish second in the AL batting race (behind teammate Norm Cash).
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] The Tigers won 101 games, to date the third-highest win total in team history, but still finished eight games behind a New York Yankees team that was led by the home run heroics of Roger Maris (61) and Mickey Mantle (54).
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Kaline began the 1962 season hitting .345 with 13 home runs and 38 RBIs in 35 games.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] On May 26 of that season, he sustained a broken collarbone while making a game-ending catch on a ball hit by New York's Elston Howard.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] He missed 57 games due to the injury and Detroit was unable to seriously compete for a pennant due to his absence.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] When healthy, Kaline was great in 1962, hitting a career-high 29 home runs and driving in 94 runs in only 100 games.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] By late March 1963, Kaline said that he felt good and he was hitting .373 in 53 spring training at-bats.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] In the 1963 regular season, Kaline hit .312 with 27 home runs and 101 RBIs, finishing second to Elston Howard in the American League's Most Valuable Player Award voting.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Kaline experienced pain in his left foot, the one that had been affected by osteomyelitis as a child, throughout the 1964 season.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] His batting average dropped to .293 that season.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Kaline tried to ignore the pain, but he saw physicians who thought he was suffering from gout and administered injections.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Still in pain the following season, Kaline saw an orthopedic surgeon who prescribed corrective shoes.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] "I feel so much better than I did before, that it's ridiculous", Kaline said by June 1965.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Sportswriter Milton Gross described Kaline's deformed foot, saying, "The pinky and middle finger don't touch the ground.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] The first and third toes overlap the second and the fourth is beginning to overlap the big toe, which has begun to bend to the left.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] In 1966, Kaline tied his career high with 29 home runs.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] In the summer of 1967, the normally calm Kaline broke a bone in his hand when he struck a baseball bat against a bat rack.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] When he returned, the Tigers were in a four-team pennant race, but the team finished the season one game behind the first place Boston Red Sox.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Kaline missed two months of the 1968 season with a broken arm, but he returned to the lineup when Tiger manager Mayo Smith benched shortstop Ray Oyler and sent center fielder Mickey Stanley to play shortstop to make room for Kaline in the outfield.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] ESPN later called Smith's move one of the ten greatest coaching decisions of the century.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Louis Cardinals won three of the first four games of the series and were leading Game 5 by a score of 3–2 in the seventh inning, when Kaline hit a bases loaded single to drive in two runs.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] The Tigers won that game, and then won Game 6 in a blowout.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Kaline had two hits, two runs scored and three RBI in the Tigers' 10-run third inning of Game 6.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Detroit went on to win Game 7 for their first world championship since 1945.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] In his only World Series appearance, Kaline hit .379 with two home runs and eight RBIs in seven games.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] For their victory, Kaline and his teammates each received bonus checks of $10,000 (at a time when Kaline's salary was "about $70,000").
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] The 1969 Tigers could not repeat the magic of their World Series triumph, as they won 90 games but still finished 19 games behind the Baltimore Orioles in the newly-formed American League East division.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Kaline hit .272 with 21 home runs in 131 games.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] It was the last season of his career that he reached 20 homers.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] In 1970, Kaline sustained a freak, near-fatal injury in an outfield collision.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] In a game at Milwaukee's County Stadium on May 30, against the Milwaukee Brewers, Kaline collided with center fielder Jim Northrup as they both pursued a fly ball.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Kaline fell to the warning track and immediately began to choke; on impact, his jaw had gotten locked and his tongue obstructed his breathing.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Alertly, left fielder Willie Horton rushed over and pried opened Kaline's mouth, clearing his airway and likely saving his life.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Kaline was carried out on a stretcher and spent the night in hospital as a precaution.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Later on, he said that he could not remember the incident.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] After hitting .294 in 1971, Kaline became the first Tiger to sign a $100,000 ($794,988 in today's dollars) contract.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] He had turned down a pay raise from $95,000 to $100,000 the previous year, saying he did not feel like he deserved it after hitting .278 with 16 home runs in 1970.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Detroit contended all season for the 1972 pennant, trailing the Red Sox by a half-game before a series against them to end the regular season.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Kaline batted eight times in two games, registering five hits and three runs scored.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Detroit won those first two games and clinched the AL East pennant.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Kaline batted .313 in 106 games in 1972, topping .300 for the first time since 1967.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] The Tigers lost the 1972 American League Championship Series to the Oakland Athletics that year after Reggie Jackson stole home in the decisive fifth game of the series.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] In March 1973, Kaline won the Roberto Clemente Award in recognition of the honor he brought to baseball on and off the field.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] On September 24, 1974, Kaline became the 12th player in MLB history to reach the 3,000 hit milestone, when he hit a double off the Orioles' Dave McNally.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] After reaching the milestone, Kaline announced that he would retire at season's end.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] I may miss spring training", Kaline said after his last game on October 3, 1974.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] In his final major league season, he was used exclusively as a designated hitter, batting .262 with 13 home runs.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] He batted over .300 nine times in his career to finish with a lifetime batting average of .297 and hit 25 or more home runs seven times in his career.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Kaline also holds Tiger career records for games played (2,834), walks (1,277), and sacrifice flies (104).
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] He had more walks than strikeouts (1,020).
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Kaline was a good pinch hitter in his career, batting .311 (37-for-119) in that capacity with two home runs and 23 RBI.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] His highest season strikeout total came in his final season, with 75.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Prior to that, Kaline never struck out more than 66 times in a season.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Among position players, Kaline ranks 29th all-time (15th among outfielders) in Wins Against Replacement (WAR) with a career mark of 92.8.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Defensively, Kaline finished his career with an overall .987 fielding percentage.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] In his first full season (1954), he recorded 16 outfield assists, including three in one game (July 7 against the Chicago White Sox).
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] He recorded 84 outfield assists between 1954 and 1958, posting a career-high 23 in 1958.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] After that season, baserunners rarely tested his arm, and his assist numbers dropped.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Kaline was elected to the Baseball Hall of Fame in 1980, becoming the tenth player in history to be inducted in his first year of eligibility.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] He was named on 340 of the 385 ballots (88.3%) cast by sportswriters.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Kaline and Duke Snider were the only candidates elected by the sportswriters in 1980.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Kaline later said, "I really never thought I would choose an individual thing that happened just to me over a team thing like the World Series.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Kaline was honored by the Tigers as the first of their players to have his uniform number (6) retired.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Versatile and well-rounded, he won ten Gold Glove Awards (1957–59 and 1961–67) for excellence in the field and appeared in the All-Star game 15 times (1955–67, 1971, 1974).
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] In 1999, Kaline was ranked number 76 on *The Sporting News* list of the 100 Greatest Baseball Players, and was nominated as a finalist for the Major League Baseball All-Century Team.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] In 2020, *The Athletic* ranked Kaline at number 51 on its "Baseball 100" list, complied by sportswriter Joe Posnanski.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] In 2022, as part of their SN Rushmore project, *The Sporting News* named Kaline on their "Detroit Mount Rushmore of Sports", along with Detroit Red Wings hockey player Gordie Howe, Detroit Lions football player Barry Sanders, and Detroit Pistons basketball player Isiah Thomas.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Cherry Street, which ran behind the left-field stands at Tiger Stadium, was renamed Kaline Drive in his honor in 1970.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] On September 27, 1999, when Detroit played its last game at Tiger Stadium against the Kansas City Royals, Kaline was invited to appear in uniform and present the last lineup card to the umpires.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] He did so along with George Brett, former Kansas City Royals' great and fellow Hall of Famer.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Kaline was regarded as a well-rounded player by his contemporaries.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Baltimore Orioles third baseman Brooks Robinson said of him, "There have been a lot of great defensive players.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] The fella who could do everything is Al Kaline.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] He was just the epitome of what a great outfielder is all about – great speed, catches the ball and throws the ball well." Manager Billy Martin once said, "I have always referred to Al Kaline as 'Mister Perfection'.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] He does it all — hitting, fielding, running, throwing — and he does it with that extra touch of brilliancy that marks him as a super ballplayer...
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] The 1993 Major League Baseball All-Star Game was dedicated to Kaline on the occasion of the 35th anniversary of his hometown's only other Midsummer Classic.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Kaline, along with Leon Day and former Baltimore Orioles star Brooks Robinson, threw out the ceremonial first pitch to end the pregame ceremonies.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Kaline's ceremonial first pitch was caught by future Detroit Tiger Ivan Rodriguez, who was starting his All-Star debut.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Starting in 2003, Kaline served as a special assistant to Tigers President/CEO/General Manager Dave Dombrowski, and his duties included coaching/mentoring outfielders during spring training.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Former Tigers teammate Willie Horton also holds this position, and the two threw out the first pitch of the 2006 World Series at Comerica Park.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Kaline continued in his assistant role until his death in 2020.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] His 67 years with one team was one of the longest tenures in MLB history.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Because of his lengthy career and longtime association with the Tigers organization, Kaline's nickname was "Mr.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Tiger." Kaline's grandson Colin Kaline was selected by the Tigers in the 25th round of the 2007 MLB draft.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] He did not sign, choosing to play baseball at Florida Southern College.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] The team drafted him again in the 2011 MLB draft, this time in the 26th round.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] He played in the low minor leagues with the Detroit organization in 2011–12.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Kaline married his high school sweetheart, Madge Louise Hamilton, in 1954.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] August 21, 1957) and Michael Keith Kaline (b.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Michael played college baseball at Miami University and is the father of Colin Kaline, who had a short Minor League career and was a college coach.
[src:first-baseman/al-kaline] Kaline died in his home in Bloomfield Hills, Michigan, on April 6, 2020; the cause of death was not reported.
[src:first-baseman/ball-boy] Quick retrieval of loose balls and delivery of the game balls to the servers are necessary for quick play in tennis.
[src:first-baseman/ball-boy] In professional tournaments, every court will have a trained squad of ball boys/girls with positionings and movements designed for maximum efficiency, while also not interfering with active play.
[src:first-baseman/ball-boy] As well as dealing with the game balls, ball boys/girls may also provide the players with other assistance, such as the delivery of towels and drinks.
[src:first-baseman/ball-boy] There are various methods for selecting the ball boys and girls for a tournament.
[src:first-baseman/ball-boy] In many tournaments, such as Wimbledon and the Queen's Club Championships, they are picked from or apply through schools, where they are selected by tournaments, and they have to go through a number of selections and tests.
[src:first-baseman/ball-boy] In some other tournaments, such as the Nottingham Open, Australian Open and the US Open, positions are advertised and there are open try-outs.
[src:first-baseman/ball-boy] Applicants are required to pass a physical ability assessment.
[src:first-baseman/ball-boy] In addition to fitness and stamina, the abilities to concentrate and remain alert are essential.
[src:first-baseman/ball-boy] In 2006, the IFAB Laws of the Game of association football were changed to allow multiple balls to be used under the direction of a referee.
[src:first-baseman/ball-boy] Higher level organised matches now commonly use 6+ balls with ball boys scattered around the pitch to quicken the pace of play.
[src:first-baseman/ball-boy] Typically positioned behind advertising boards surrounding the pitch, ball boys will try to be in possession of a spare ball at all times, so that this can be given to the players prior to the loose ball being retrieved.
[src:first-baseman/ball-boy] Balls may also be stored on cones near sidelines, so that they are readily available for restarts, and to prevent ball boys from accelerating returns to home players, and delaying returns to away players.
[src:first-baseman/ball-boy] Methods for selecting ball boys vary between grounds.
[src:first-baseman/ball-boy] On occasion, away teams have complained about perceived favour of ball boys towards home sides.
[src:first-baseman/ball-boy] In a 2013 EFL Cup match Eden Hazard, a member of the away team, which was trailing at the time, got into an altercation with an apparently time-wasting ball boy who was lying on top of the ball.
[src:first-baseman/ball-boy] Hazard was subsequently sent off for violent conduct and suspended for three games.
[src:first-baseman/ball-boy] Ball kids are stationed in out-of-play areas near the first and third base foul lines to retrieve out-of-play baseballs.
[src:first-baseman/ball-boy] They should not be confused with bat boys and bat girls, who remain in or near a team's dugout and the home plate area, primarily to tend to a team's baseball bats.
[src:first-baseman/ball-boy] As ball kids are stationed on the field, albeit in foul territory, they can occasionally interfere with play; such events are governed by Rule 6.01(d), the main point of which is that if the interference is unintentional, any live ball remains alive and in play.
[src:first-baseman/ball-boy] For this reason, most teams will use experienced individuals who understand the rules, to minimize mistaken interference.
[src:first-baseman/ball-boy] One of the more infamous examples was the use of a Hooters girl as a promotion.
[src:first-baseman/ball-boy] The woman unfortunately snagged a ball that was fair and live in a Tampa Bay Rays game, throwing it to the fans.
[src:first-baseman/ball-boy] The batter was awarded a double on the interference.
[src:first-baseman/ball-boy] Since 1992, the San Francisco Giants have employed older men as "balldudes", instead of the traditional youths.
[src:first-baseman/ball-boy] In 1993, Corinne Mullane became the first "balldudette", and she and her daughter Molly, who began working as a balldudette in the 2000s, have since been included in the National Baseball Hall of Fame as the first mother-daughter ball-retrieving duo in baseball.
[src:first-baseman/ball-boy] Ball boys are stationed around the field just outside the boundary to retrieve any balls struck into the spectator stands or to the boundary rope.
[src:first-baseman/ball-boy] In India, disabled people are not allowed to be ball-boys anymore after a controversy occurred in 2017, after criticism of the Board of Control for Cricket in India surrounding the appearance of a polio-afflicted fan who had been serving as a ball-boy for a few years.
[src:first-baseman/base-running] In baseball, **base running** is the act of running from base to base, performed by members of the team at bat.
[src:first-baseman/base-running] Base running is a tactical part of the game with the goal of eventually reaching home base (home plate) to score a run.
[src:first-baseman/base-running] Batters strive to become base runners, and to enable existing base runners to move to a subsequent base or to score.
[src:first-baseman/base-running] In statistics, the number of baserunners (for example those allowed by a pitcher) is denoted by the abbreviation **BR**.
[src:first-baseman/base-running] The Official Baseball Rules uses the term **batter-runner** to identify the batter from the time he becomes a base runner until the end of the same play, whether he is successful at legally attaining first base or any subsequent base.
[src:first-baseman/base-running] The term is not applied if the batter is awarded first base (the last three items in the above list).
[src:first-baseman/base-running] If a base runner's teammate is put out for the third out of the inning, the base runner is said to be left on base (LOB).
[src:first-baseman/base-running] A runner who is touching a base which he is entitled to occupy may not be tagged out.
[src:first-baseman/base-running] Runners may attempt to advance from base to base on any fair ball that touches the ground.
[src:first-baseman/base-running] When a ball is hit in the air (i.e., a *fly ball*) and caught by the defending team, runners must return and touch the base they occupy—called *tagging up*—after the ball is first touched by a fielder.
[src:first-baseman/base-running] Once they do this, they may attempt to advance at their own risk.
[src:first-baseman/base-running] On a ball that touches the ground in fair territory, if there is a force, runners are required to run.
[src:first-baseman/base-running] Base runners may attempt to advance at any time while the ball is alive, even before or while the pitcher is throwing a pitch.
[src:first-baseman/base-running] The catcher—or pitcher, in lieu of delivering the pitch—often tries to prevent this by throwing the ball to one of the infielders in order to tag the runner.
[src:first-baseman/base-running] This *pick-off attempt* is usually unsuccessful in tagging out the runner but is effective in keeping the runner closer to the base.
[src:first-baseman/base-running] If the runner is tagged out while diving back to the base, it is called a *pickoff*.
[src:first-baseman/base-running] If the runner attempts to advance to the next base but is tagged out before reaching it safely, he is *caught stealing*.
[src:first-baseman/base-running] A successful attempt by the runner is called a *stolen base*.
[src:first-baseman/base-running] If a pitch gets away from the catcher, runners may also try to advance.
[src:first-baseman/base-running] This may be a *wild pitch*, if the pitcher is held responsible for the ball getting away, or a *passed ball* if the catcher is deemed to be at fault.
[src:first-baseman/base-running] Sometimes the defending team will ignore a runner who is trying to steal a base; in this case a runner is not credited with a steal, and the base is attributed to *defensive indifference*.
[src:first-baseman/base-running] An infielder who cleanly fields a ball hit on the ground, then throws it quickly and accurately, will usually get the ball to a base before the runner runs the 90 feet (27 m).
[src:first-baseman/base-running] However, any hesitation or mistake on the part of the fielder may allow the runner to reach the base safely.
[src:first-baseman/base-running] Teams scout the opposition and take advantage of players who are poor at defense.
[src:first-baseman/base-running] For example, on a deep fly ball to center field with a man on second base, if the center fielder has a weak arm, the runner on second base may tag the base and attempt to reach third despite the risks of being tagged out.
[src:first-baseman/base-running] Base running and hitting are coordinated to produce better results in the squeeze play and the hit and run play.
[src:first-baseman/base-running] When the count is full and there are two outs, any runners forced to advance begin running as soon as the pitcher's motion obliges him to complete his pitch, as their distance from the base will not be the cause of any third out.
[src:first-baseman/base-running] Good runners also try to get extra bases when a play is being made at a different base.
[src:first-baseman/base-running] For example, a batter who hits a single should determine whether the defense's focus on another runner gives the batter a chance to reach second base.
[src:first-baseman/base-running] Sliding into a base is an important part of base running.
[src:first-baseman/base-running] The pop-up slide both ensures that the runner touches the base and elevates him to an upright posture to help him take additional bases if the defense misperforms.
[src:first-baseman/base-running] A take-out slide tries to use a collision with a fielder to keep him from taking additional action, such as throwing to achieve a double play.
[src:first-baseman/base-running] However, this move, when made independently of the attempt to reach the base, has been illegal since 2016 because of the potential for injury.
[src:first-baseman/base-running] The base coach at third base, and any batter still at home plate, may watch the ball approaching the base and may signal the base runner on the optimum slide to avoid being tagged out.
[src:first-baseman/base-running] The most baserunners allowed by a pitcher in a game since 1901 is 39, by Eddie Rommel, who pitched 17 innings in relief for the Philadelphia Athletics to defeat the Cleveland Indians, 18–17, on July 10, 1932.
[src:first-baseman/base-running] The record number of baserunners in a season is 820, by John Coleman of the Philadelphia Quakers in 1883.
[src:first-baseman/base-running] Wilbur Wood of the 1973 Chicago White Sox was the last pitcher to allow more than 500 baserunners in a season.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] A **baseball field**, also called a **ball field** or **baseball diamond**, is the field upon which the game of baseball is played.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] The term can also be used as a metonym for a baseball park.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] The term **sandlot** is sometimes used, although this usually refers to less organized venues for activities like sandlot ball.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] The starting point for much of the action on the field is home plate (officially "home base"), a five-sided slab of white rubber.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] One side is 17 inches (43 cm) long, the two adjacent sides are 8.5 inches (22 cm).
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] The remaining two sides are approximately 12 inches (30 cm) and set at a right angle.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] The plate is set into the ground so that its surface is level with the field.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] The corner of home plate where the two 12-inch sides meet at a right angle is at one corner of a 90-foot (27.43 m) square.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] The dimensional specifications are technically inconsistent because the angle constraints require that the front be √2 times the length of the back, which is not equal to a 17:12 ratio, but a physically built home plate will have side lengths accurate to a few hundredths of an inch.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] The other three corners of the square, in counterclockwise order from home plate, are called first, second, and third base.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] These bases are marked by canvas or rubber cushions, 18 inches (46 cm) square and 3–5 inches (7.6–12.7 cm) thick.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Adjacent to each of the two parallel 8.5-inch sides is a batter's box.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] All the bases, including home plate, lie entirely within fair territory.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Thus, any batted ball that touches those bases must necessarily be ruled a fair ball.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] While the first and third base bags are placed so that they lie inside the 90-foot square formed by the bases, the second base bag is placed so that its center (unlike first, third and home) coincides exactly with the "point" of the ninety-foot square.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Thus, although the "points" of the bases are 90 feet apart, the physical distance between each successive pair of base markers is closer to 88 feet (26.8 m).
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Near the center of the square is an artificial hill known as the pitcher's mound, atop which is a white rubber slab known as the pitcher's plate, colloquially the "rubber" because of its physical composition.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] The specifications for the pitcher's mound are described below.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] The lines from home plate to first and third bases extend to the nearest fence, stand or other obstruction and are called the foul lines.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] The portion of the playing field between (and including) the foul lines is fair territory; the rest is "foul territory".
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] The area within the square formed by the bases is officially called the infield, though colloquially this term also includes fair territory in the vicinity of the square; fair territory outside the infield is known as the outfield.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Most baseball fields are enclosed with a fence that marks the outer edge of the outfield.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] The fence is usually set at a distance ranging from 300 to 420 feet (90 to 130 m) from home plate.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Most professional and college baseball fields have a right and left foul pole which are about 440 to 500 feet (130 to 150 m) apart.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] These poles are at the intersection of the foul lines and the respective ends of the outfield fence and, unless otherwise specified within the ground rules, lie in fair territory.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Thus, a batted ball that passes over the outfield wall in flight and touches the foul pole is a fair ball and the batter is awarded a home run.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] A baseball infield is the square area within the four 90-foot baselines "(60-foot baselines in Little League Baseball for youths 12 years old and under)".
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] The four bases are integral parts of the infield; a ball that touches any part of a base is considered a fair ball.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] First base is the first of the four bases that must be touched by a runner in order to score a run for the batting team.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] The runner may continue running past first base in a straight line without being in jeopardy of being put out, so long as they make contact with first base and make no move or attempt to advance to second base.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] The first baseman is the defensive player mainly responsible for the area near first base.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] In some youth leagues and adult recreational leagues, a "double first base" or "safety first base" is used.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] A double first base is rectangular (rather than square), measuring 30 by 15 inches.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] It is normally colored white and orange (two 15 by 15 inches squares).
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] It is placed with the white half in fair territory and the orange half in foul territory.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] The white half is used by the first baseman to make plays while the orange half is used by the runner.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] This creates a separation between the first baseman and runner, reducing the chance of injury on plays at first base.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] In the numbering system used to record defensive plays, the first baseman is assigned the number 3.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Second base is the second of the four bases a runner must touch in order to score a run.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Second base is mainly defended by the second baseman and the shortstop.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] The second baseman and shortstop ideally possess quick reactions and the ability to release the ball rapidly and accurately.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] One player will usually cover second base while the other attempts to field the ball.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Both players must communicate well to be able to make a double play.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Particular agility is required of the second baseman in many double play situations, which frequently force the player receiving a throw from the shortstop to immediately throw towards first base while their momentum typically carries them towards third base.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] A runner on second base is said to be in "scoring position", since there is a higher likelihood of scoring a run from second base on a single than there is from first base.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Since second base is the farthest from home plate, it is the most commonly stolen base in baseball.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] In the numbering system used to record defensive plays, the second baseman is assigned the number 4, and the shortstop 6.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Third base is the third of the four bases a runner must touch in order to score a run.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] The third baseman is the defensive player mainly responsible for the area nearest third base.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] A third baseman ideally possesses quick reaction to batted balls and a strong throwing arm to make the long throw to first base.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Third base is sometimes referred to as the "hot corner" as it's common for right-handed batters to hit the ball hard to third base, occasionally making successfully fielding the ball difficult.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] In the numbering system used to record defensive plays, the third baseman is assigned the number 5.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Like a runner on second base, a runner on third base is said to be in "scoring position", since there is a higher likelihood of scoring a run on any hit, a sacrifice fly, and many other plays, provided that the third and final out is not recorded before they can reach home plate.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Home base, called "home plate", is the final base that a player must touch to score a run.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Unlike the other bases, home plate is a five-sided slab of white rubber that is set at ground level.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] In most MLB stadiums, the backstop is at least 60 feet behind home plate and is composed of a lower solid wall and upper netting that protects spectators behind home plate from wild pitches, passed balls, and foul balls.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] In recreational fields, there is usually a tall chain-link fence that surrounds the infield and the players' bench for player safety.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Baselines are straight lines between two adjacent bases normally made of chalk.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Physical baselines are not drawn between first and second or second and third bases; the foul lines serve to mark the baseline between home plate and first base, and between third base and home.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Generally, baserunners are not required to follow the baseline.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] A baserunner seeking to advance more than one base typically "rounds" the base, following a more circular path.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] However, a runner's avoidance maneuvers are constrained when the defense tries to tag him.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] At the moment the defense begins the attempt, the baserunner's running baseline is established as a direct line from his current position to the base he is trying for.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] A runner straying more than three feet (1 m) away from this baseline to avoid a tag may be called out.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Beginning halfway between home and first base, and ending at first base, there is a second chalk line to the right of the foul line.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] This second line and the part of the foul line it runs parallel to, form the running lane that defines the path in which a batter-runner must run as he is advancing to first base.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Rule 6.05(k) of the Official Baseball Rules states that if a batter-runner running to first base runs outside the running lane, and "in doing so" interferes with the fielder taking the throw at first, then the batter-runner is automatically out.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] First base itself is not located in the running lane, but Rule 6.05 lets the batter-runner leave the running lane "by means of a step, stride or slide in the immediate vicinity of first base" to step on first base.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] The batter's box is the place where the batter stands when ready to receive a pitch from the pitcher.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] It is usually drawn in chalk on the dirt surrounding home plate, and the insides of the boxes are watered down before each game.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] The chalk lines delineating the two foul lines are rarely extended through the batter's boxes.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] However, those lines exist conceptually for the purpose of judging a batted ball fair or foul.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] In addition, inside edges of the batter's boxes are often not laid-in with chalk.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Similarly, though not marked, those lines continue to exist for the purpose of the rules pertaining to the batter's box and the batter's position relative thereto.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] There are two batter's boxes, one on each side of home plate.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] The batter's boxes are 4 feet (1.22 m) wide and 6 feet (1.83 m) long.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] The batter's boxes are centered lengthwise at the center of home plate with the inside line of each batter's box 6 inches (15 cm) from the near edge of home plate.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] A right-handed batter would stand in the batter's box on the right side of home plate from the perspective of the pitcher.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] A left-handed batter would stand in the batter's box to their left.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] A batter may only occupy one batter's box at a time and may not legally leave the batter's box after the pitcher has come set or has started their windup.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Should the batter wish to leave the batter's box once the pitcher has engaged the rubber, they must first ask the umpire for time-out.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Time will not be granted if the pitcher has already started their pitching motion.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] For playing rules relating to the batter's box, see Rules 6.05 and 6.06 of the Official Baseball Rules.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] The catcher's box is an area of the field behind home plate which the catcher occupies to avoid committing a balk when a pitch is thrown.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] In roughly the middle of the diamond, equidistant between first and third base, and a few feet closer to home plate than to second base, is a low artificial hill called the pitcher's mound.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] This is where the pitcher stands when throwing the pitch.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Atop the mound is a white rubber slab, called the pitcher's plate or pitcher's rubber.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] It measures 6 inches (15 cm) front-to-back and 2 feet (61 cm) across, the front of which is exactly 60 feet 6 inches (18.44 m) from the rear point of home plate.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] This peculiar distance was set by the rule makers in 1893, not due to a clerical or surveying error as popular myth has it, but intentionally (further details under *History*).
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] In Major League Baseball, a regulation mound is 18 feet (5.5 m) in diameter, with the center 59 feet (18 m) from the rear point of home plate, on the line between home plate and second base.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] The front edge of the *pitcher's plate* or *rubber* is 18 inches (46 cm) behind the center of the mound, making the front edge's midpoint 60 feet 6 inches from the rear point of home plate. six inches (15 cm) in front of the pitcher's rubber the mound begins to slope downward.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] The top of the rubber is to be no higher than ten inches (25 cm) above home plate.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] From 1903 through 1968, this height limit was set at 15 inches (38 cm), but in reality differed from ballpark to ballpark as the height was considered too difficult to enforce.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] A higher mound generally favors the pitcher, and teams that emphasize pitching (such as the Los Angeles Dodgers) will favor a slightly higher mound.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] With the height advantage, the pitcher gains more leverage and can put more downward velocity on the ball, making it more difficult for the batter to strike the ball squarely with the bat.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] After 1968, known among baseball historians as "the year of the pitcher", the official height of the mound was lowered from 15 to 10 inches (38 to 25 cm) in an attempt to "increase the batting" once again.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] A pitcher's mound is difficult for groundskeepers to maintain.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Usually before every game it is watered down to keep the dust from spreading.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] On youth and amateur baseball fields, the mound may be much different from the rule book definition due to erosion and repair attempts.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Even in the major leagues, each mound gains its own character, as pitchers are allowed to kick away pieces of dirt in their way, thereby sculpting the mound a bit to their preference.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] The pitcher may keep a rosin bag on the rear of the mound to dry off their hands.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Major League Baseball teams are also permitted cleat cleaners on the back of the mound.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] This may be a flat grate-style plate, or simply a hand tool such as a piece of wood used to remove mud and dirt from cleats.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] These items are allowed to remain on the backside of the mound at the discretion of the umpire, thus reducing the probability that they will affect a live play.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Dirt running paths between the bases (and at one time, and still in some parks, between the pitcher and the catcher) have existed since the beginning of the game, although they were not mentioned in the rule books until around 1950, and their specifications are flexible.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] In addition to providing a running path, the grass lines act as a visual aid so that players, umpires and fans may better judge distance from the center of the diamond.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Occasionally the ball may take a tricky bounce off the dirt area or the edge between the dirt and the grass.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Multiple World Series championships (including 1924 and 1960) have been influenced by erratic hops of ground balls.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] In artificial turf stadiums, infield dirt was originally only placed in three five-sided areas around the bases and in two circles around the pitcher's and batting areas, which are referred to as "cutouts".
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] In this configuration, the "grass line" is usually designated with a white arc.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] This setup first appeared at Cincinnati's Riverfront Stadium upon its opening in 1970.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Among Major League Baseball fields, Rogers Centre was the last stadium to maintain this type of configuration and was reconfigured with a full dirt infield starting in the 2016 MLB season.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] In some college baseball parks with artificial turf fields, the entire field (along with possibly the pitcher's mound) is made up of turf, with parts of the field mainly containing dirt instead merely being clay-colored turf.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] The outfield is made from shortly-trimmed grass or artificial turf.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] The positions to play in the outfield are left, center, and right field (named in relation to the batter's position; thus left field is beyond third base and right field is beyond first base).
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Outfields vary in size and shape depending on the overall size and shape of the playing field.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] The outfield stretches from the infield to the outfield wall and it contains the warning track.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Outfields especially vary from Little League to major league fields.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Little League outfields vary more in size than Major League outfields.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Outfields often differ from infields in the specific type of grass used, but most major league outfields are grass.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] The warning track is the strip of dirt at the edges of the baseball field (especially in front of the home run fence and along the left and right sides of a field).
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Because the warning track's color and feel differ from the grass field, a fielder can remain focused on a fly ball near the fence and measure their proximity to the fence while attempting to catch the ball safely.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] A warning track's width is not specified in the rules.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] It is generally designed to give about three steps of warning to the highest-level players using the field.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Typical widths run from about six feet for Little League fields to about 10–15 feet (3.0–4.6 meters) for college- or professional-level play.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] A warning track this wide also lets groundskeepers avoid driving maintenance vehicles on the grass.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] The track can be composed of finely ground rock particles such as cinders, which is why announcer Bob Wolff called it the "cinder path" rather than the "warning track".
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] The idea of a warning track originated in Yankee Stadium, where an actual running track was built for use in track and field events.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] When ballpark designers saw how the track helped fielders, it soon became a feature of every ballpark.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Fielders often knowingly risk injury crashing into a wall trying to make a catch despite the warning track.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] For this reason, outfield walls are typically padded for extra safety.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Wrigley Field's brick wall is covered only by ivy, which is not especially soft.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] However, there are pads on the walls of the tight left and right field corners in foul ground.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] The outfield wall or fence is the outer boundary of the outfield.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] If it passes over the wall in fair territory, without touching the ground, it is a home run.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] As a result, baseball fields can vary greatly along those lines.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] The wall has numbers affixed or painted on it that denote the distance from that point on the wall to home plate.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] In most modern major league ballparks, the wall is made of some hard material (e.g., concrete, plywood, sheet metal) with padding on the field side to protect players who may collide with the wall at high speed while trying to make a play.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Chain link fencing may also be incorporated into the wall in areas where the wall needs to be transparent, e.g., an outfield bullpen, a spectator area behind the wall, or to protect a scoreboard incorporated into the wall.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Many ballparks feature a yellow line denoting the top of the wall to aid umpires in judging whether the ball passed over the wall or if the ball is fair or foul.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Foul poles, if present, help umpires judge whether a fly ball hit above the fence line is foul (out of play) or fair (a home run).
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] The poles are a vertical extension of the foul lines at the edge of the field of play.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] The outer edge of the foul lines and foul poles define foul territory.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] **Both the lines and the poles are actually in fair territory**, in contrast to American football and basketball, where the lines marking the playing boundaries are out of bounds.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] The minimum distance to hit a home run (along either foul line) is set by baseball rules, generally at 325 feet (99 m).
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Before 1931 (with the exception of a couple months in 1920) the foul lines extended indefinitely; a batter was awarded a home run only if a fly ball out of the field was fair where it landed.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Now, a batted ball that leaves the field in flight is judged fair or foul at the point it leaves the field.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Thus, such a fly ball passing on the fair side of a foul pole, or hitting a foul pole, is a home run regardless of where the ball goes thereafter.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Foul poles are typically much higher than the top of the outfield fence or wall, and often have a narrow screen running along the fair side of the pole.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] This further aids the umpires' judgment, as a ball that bounces off this screen is a home run.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] It can still be a difficult call, especially in ballparks with no outfield stands behind the poles to provide perspective.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Wrigley Field is notorious for arguments over long, curving flies down a foul line (most notably in left field) that sail higher than the foul pole.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] At Major League Baseball fields, foul poles are usually yellow.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] At Petco Park, there is no foul pole in left field; the pole's function is served by a yellow metal strip along the corner of the Western Metal Supply Co. building.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Several parks featuring advertising along the length of the foul pole, with the most prominent example being the advertising from Chick-fil-A at both Citi Field and Daikin Park (serving as a pun, with "fowl" being another term for a chicken, the primary meat featured by that restaurant chain).
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] The bullpen (sometimes referred to as simply "the 'pen") is the area where pitchers warm up before entering a game.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Depending on the ballpark, it may be situated in foul territory along the baselines or just beyond the outfield fence.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Relief pitchers usually wait in the bullpen when they have yet to play in a game, rather than in the dugout with the rest of the team.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] The starting pitcher also makes their final pregame warmups in the bullpen.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Managers can call coaches in the bullpen on an in-house telephone from the dugout to tell a certain pitcher to begin their warmup tosses.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] "Bullpen" is also used metonymically to describe a team's collection of relief pitchers.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] There are two on-deck circles in the field, one for each team, positioned in foul ground between home plate and the respective teams' benches.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] The on-deck circle is where the next scheduled batter, or "on-deck" batter, warms up while waiting for the current batter to finish their turn.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] The on-deck circle is either an area composed of bare dirt; a plain circle painted onto artificial turf; or often, especially at the professional level, a mat made from artificial material, with the team or league logo painted onto it.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] The coach's boxes, located behind first and third base, are where the first and third base coaches are supposed to stand, although coaches often stand outside the box.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] This is permissible as long as the coach does not interfere with play and the opposing team does not object (in which case the umpire shall ensure that all coaches on both teams must abide by the boundaries of the coach's boxes).
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] The coach's boxes are marked with chalk or paint.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] In the early days of baseball, the term "coacher's box" was used, as "coach" was taken to be a verb.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] As the term "coach" evolved into a noun, the name of the box also changed.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] The basic layout of the field has been little changed since the Knickerbocker Rules of the 1840s.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Those rules specified the distance from home to second as 42 "paces".
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] The dictionary definition of a "pace" at the time was 30 inches, yielding base paths of approximately 75 feet; however, if a "pace" of three feet was meant then the distance would have been 89 feet.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] It is not implausible that the early clubs simply stepped off the distance.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] 30 yards (90 feet) between the bases was first explicitly prescribed by the NABBP Convention of 1857.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Through trial and error, 90 feet had been settled upon as the optimal distance.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] 100 feet would have given too much advantage to the defense, and 80 feet too much to the offense.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] The original Knickerbocker Rules did not specify the pitching distance explicitly; the 1854 Unified Rules stated "from Home to pitcher not less than fifteen paces".
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] By the time major league baseball began in the 1870s, the pitcher was compelled to pitch from within a "box" whose front edge was 45 feet (14 m) from the "point" of home plate.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Although they had to release the ball before crossing the line, as with bowlers in cricket, they also had to start their delivery from within the box, meaning that they could only run for a short distance before throwing; they could not run in from the field as bowlers do.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Furthermore, the pitcher had to throw underhand.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] By the 1880s, pitchers had mastered the underhand delivery—in fact, in 1880, there were two perfect games within a week of each other.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] In an attempt to "increase the batting", the front edge of the pitcher's box was moved back 5 feet in 1881, to 50 feet (15 m) from home plate.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] The size of the box was altered over the following few years.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Pitchers were allowed to throw overhand starting in 1884, and that tilted the balance of power again.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] In 1887, the box was set at 4 feet (1.2 m) wide and 5.5 feet (1.7 m) deep, with the front edge still 50 feet from the plate.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] However, the pitcher was compelled to deliver the ball with their back foot at the 55.5-foot (16.9 m) line of the box, thus somewhat restricting their ability to "power" the ball with their overhand delivery.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] In 1893, the box was replaced by the pitcher's plate, although "the box" is still used today as a slang term for the pitcher's location on the field.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Exactly 5 feet was added to the point the pitcher had to toe, again "to increase the batting" (and hopefully to increase attendance, as fan interest had flagged somewhat), resulting in the seemingly peculiar pitching distance of 60.5 feet (18.44 m).
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Some sources suggest that the pitching distance evolved from 45 to 50 to 60.5 feet.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] However, the first two were the "release point" and the third is the "pushoff point." The 1893 rule change added only 5 feet to the release point, not 10.5 feet.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Originally the pitcher threw from flat ground.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Gradually, the raised mound was developed, somewhat returning the advantage to the pitchers.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] From 1893 to 1950, a stipulation was added that the mound be no more than 15 inches above the field.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Before the mid-20th century, it was common for baseball fields to include a dirt pathway between the pitcher's mound and home plate.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] This feature is sometimes known as the "keyhole" due to the shape that it makes together with the mound.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] The keyhole was once as wide as the pitcher's box and resembled a cricket pitch.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Sometimes this path extended through the batting area and all the way to the backstop.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Once the rounded pitcher's mound was developed, the path became more ornamental than practical, and was gradually thinned before being largely abandoned by the 1950s.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] In recent years some ballparks, such as Comerica Park and Chase Field in the major leagues, have revived the feature for nostalgic reasons.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] From 1857 to 1867 home plate was a circular iron plate, painted or enameled white, covering "a space equal to one square foot of surface", i.e. with a diameter of ~13-1/2 inches.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] In 1868 the plate was changed to a square, 12" on a side, originally set with the flat sides toward the pitcher and catcher; the new professional National Association rotated it 45 degrees in 1871.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] In 1872 the rules required it to be made of white marble or stone set flush with the ground.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] For the rest of the century materials varied between stone, iron and wood, but at all times it was a white twelve-inch square.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] The pentagonal shape and the mandatory use of rubber were developed by Robert Keating, who had pitched one game for the 1887 Baltimore Orioles; the new plate was adopted by the National League in 1900.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] From 1861 to 1874 the center, not the back, of the plate was situated on the intersection of the foul lines, and in 1875–76 was moved entirely into foul ground with the "pitcher's point" at the intersection.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] In 1877 it was moved forward to its modern location, wholly in fair territory.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] There were no batters' boxes before 1874.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Up until that time, the batter was required to hit with their front foot on a line passing through the center of the plate.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] The Sports Turf Managers Association (STMA) presents various awards each year.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] Starting in 2001, its Sports Turf Manager of the Year Awards have been presented annually in the Triple-A, Double-A, Class A, and Short-Season/Rookie divisions of Minor League Baseball and are chosen from the 16 league winners.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-diamond] STMA also presents the Baseball Field of the Year Award, which includes Schools and Parks, College/University and Professional categories.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-glove] A **baseball glove** or **mitt** is a large glove worn by baseball players of the defending team, which assists players in catching and fielding balls hit by a batter or thrown by a teammate.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-glove] Gloves are traditionally made of leather, but today other options exist, such as PVC and synthetic leather.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-glove] By convention, the glove is described by the handedness of the intended wearer, rather than the hand on which the glove is worn: a glove that fits on the left hand—used by a right-handed thrower—is called a *right-handed* (RH) or "right-hand throw" (RHT) glove.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-glove] Conversely, a left-handed glove (LH or LHT) is worn on the right hand, allowing the player to throw the ball with the left hand.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-glove] Early baseball was a game played without gloves.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-glove] During the gradual transition to gloves, a player who continued to play without one was called a *barehanded catcher;* this did not refer to the position of catcher, but rather to the practice of catching with bare hands.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-glove] The earliest glove was not webbed and not particularly well suited for catching but was used more to swat a ball to the ground so that it could be picked up.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-glove] One of the first players believed to have used a baseball glove was Doug Allison, a catcher for the Cincinnati Red Stockings, in 1870, due to an injured left hand.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-glove] The first confirmed glove use was by Charlie Waitt, a St.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-glove] Louis outfielder and first baseman who, in 1875, donned a pair of flesh-colored gloves.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-glove] Glove use slowly caught on as more and more players began using different forms of gloves.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-glove] Many early baseball gloves were simple leather gloves with the fingertips cut off, supposedly to allow for the same control of a bare hand but with extra padding.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-glove] For the first two decades of professional baseball, these types of gloves were worn primarily by catchers, who sustained frequent hand injuries to such a point that duties for catching typically alternated each day at a time when field positions did not carry backups.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-glove] The catcher's mitt, a glove designed to be much larger than the hand and to cover it entirely, were offered for sale for the first time in 1890.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-glove] Pitcher, first baseman and outfielder Albert Spalding, originally skeptical of glove use, influenced more infielders to begin using gloves.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-glove] Spalding later founded the sporting goods company Spalding, which still manufactures baseball gloves, along with other sports equipment.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-glove] By the mid-1890s, it was normal for players to wear gloves in the field.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-glove] In the early 1900s baseball glove manufacturers started experimenting with a "full web" or "web-pocketed" gloves, gloves with a small 0.5" ~ 1" piece of leather connecting the thumb and index finger.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-glove] Unlike current webbing, this was often made of a single piece of leather fully connected to both fingers of the glove, not with strips of leather connecting both sides of the glove as would be seen starting in the 1920s.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-glove] In 1920, Bill Doak, a pitcher for the St.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-glove] Louis Cardinals, suggested that a web be placed between the first finger and the thumb in order to create a pocket.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-glove] This design soon became the standard for baseball gloves.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-glove] Doak patented his design and sold it to Rawlings.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-glove] His design became the precursor to modern gloves and enabled Rawlings to become the preferred glove of professional players.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-glove] For many years, it was customary for fielders to leave their gloves on the field when their team went in to bat.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-glove] This practice was prohibited by the major leagues in 1954.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-glove] Baseball gloves have grown progressively larger since their inception.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-glove] While catching in baseball had always been two-handed, gloves eventually grew to a size that made it easier to catch the ball in the webbing of the glove, using the off-hand to keep the ball from falling out.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-glove] A glove is typically worn on the non-dominant hand, leaving the dominant hand for the more strenuous and precise task of throwing the ball; for example, a right-handed player would wear a glove on their left hand, which would still be referred to as a "right handed glove".
[src:first-baseman/baseball-glove] The shape and size of the baseball glove are governed by official baseball rules.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-glove] Section 3.00 - Equipment and Uniforms specifies glove dimensions and materials in parts 3.04 through 3.07.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-glove] The structure and quality of the baseball glove have developed greatly over the past century.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-glove] Today, the production of baseball gloves is much more precise and efficient.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-glove] This has greatly increased the usefulness and accessibility of baseball gloves to the general population.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-glove] Currently, Easton is "experimenting with combining leather and Kevlar (used in bullet-proof vests) in a new ultra-lightweight glove line".
[src:first-baseman/baseball-glove] Manufacturers have also designed new, non-traditional types of gloves to suit non-traditional players.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-glove] Also, manufacturers are personalizing gloves for high-caliber players to help increase their exposure on national television.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-glove] Although there have been numerous advances in baseball glove design, the greatest arguably came with the advent of the catcher's mitt.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-glove] Yet despite state-of-the-art mitts being used by catchers, a Wake Forest University study of 36 U.S. minor-league players demonstrated that the mitts did not offer enough protection from hand and wrist injuries.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-glove] The highest-quality baseball gloves are typically made of heavy leather.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-glove] These leather gloves usually take more time for the player to break in.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-glove] They also provide a tighter, more personalized fit for the player.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-glove] This is an improvement from youth and recreational gloves, which tend to feature palm pads and/or adjustable Velcro wrist straps.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-glove] These gloves take less time to break in or are pre-broken in, are less personal and more "one size fits all".
[src:first-baseman/baseball-glove] Baseball gloves are measured by starting at the top of the index finger of the glove and measuring down the finger, along the inside of the pocket and then out to the heel of the glove.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-glove] Gloves typically range in size from 9 inches (229 mm) (youth starter size) to 12+3⁄4 inches (324 mm) for adult outfield play.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-glove] Catcher's mitts, unlike those of other gloves, are measured around the circumference, and they typically have 32-to-34-inch (813–864 mm) patterns.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-glove] The shape and size of a glove are described by its pattern.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The initial objective of the batting team is to have a player reach first base safely; this occurs either when the batter hits the ball and reaches first base before an opponent retrieves the ball and touches the base, or when the pitcher persists in throwing the ball out of the batter's reach.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Players on the batting team who reach first base without being called "out" can attempt to advance to subsequent bases as a runner, either immediately or during teammates' turns batting.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The fielding team tries to prevent runs by using the ball to get batters or runners "out", which forces them out of the field of play.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The pitcher can get the batter out by throwing three pitches which result in strikes, while fielders can get the batter out by catching a batted ball before it touches the ground, and can get a runner out by tagging them with the ball while the runner is not touching a base.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The opposing teams switch back and forth between batting and fielding; the batting team's turn to bat is over once the fielding team records three outs.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] One turn batting for each team constitutes an inning.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] A game is usually composed of nine innings, and the team with the greater number of runs at the end of the game wins.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Most games end after the ninth inning, but if scores are tied at that point, extra innings are usually played.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Baseball has no game clock, though some competitions feature pace-of-play regulations such as a pitch clock to shorten game time.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Baseball evolved from older bat-and-ball games already being played in England by the mid-18th century.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] This game was brought by immigrants to North America, where the modern version developed.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] In addition to North America, baseball spread throughout the rest of the Americas and the Asia–Pacific in the 19th and 20th centuries, and is now considered the most popular sport in parts of Central and South America, the Caribbean, and East Asia, particularly in Japan, South Korea, and Taiwan.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] In Major League Baseball (MLB), the highest level of professional baseball in the United States and Canada, teams are divided into the National League (NL) and American League (AL), each with three divisions: East, West, and Central.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The MLB champion is determined by playoffs that culminate in the World Series.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The top level of play is similarly split in Japan between the Central and Pacific Leagues and in Cuba between the West League and East League.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The World Baseball Classic, organized by the World Baseball Softball Confederation, is the major international competition of the sport and attracts the top national teams from around the world.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Baseball was played at the Olympic Games from 1992 to 2008, and was reinstated on a one-off basis in 2020.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] A baseball game is played between two teams, each composed of nine players, that take turns playing offense (batting and baserunning) and defense (pitching and fielding).
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] A pair of turns, one at bat and one in the field, by each team constitutes an inning.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] A game consists of nine innings (seven innings at the high school level and in doubleheaders in college and Minor League Baseball; and six innings at the Little League level).
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] One team—customarily the visiting team—bats in the top, or first half, of every inning.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The other team—customarily the home team—bats in the bottom, or second half, of every inning.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The goal of the game is to score more points (runs) than the other team.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The players on the team at bat attempt to score runs by touching all four bases, in order, set at the corners of the square-shaped baseball diamond.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] A player bats at home plate and must attempt to safely reach a base before proceeding, counterclockwise, from first base, to second base, third base, and back home to score a run.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The team in the field attempts to prevent runs from scoring by recording outs, which remove opposing players from offensive action until their next turn at bat comes up again.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] When three outs are recorded, the teams switch roles for the next half-inning.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] If the score of the game is tied after nine innings, extra innings are played to resolve the contest.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Many amateur games, particularly unorganized ones, involve different numbers of players and innings.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The game is played on a field whose primary boundaries, the foul lines, extend forward from home plate at 45-degree angles.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The 90-degree area within the foul lines is referred to as fair territory; the 270-degree area outside them is foul territory.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The part of the field enclosed by the bases and several yards beyond them is the infield; the area farther beyond the infield is the outfield.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] In the middle of the infield is a raised pitcher's mound, with a rectangular rubber plate (the rubber) at its center.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The outer boundary of the outfield is typically demarcated by a raised fence, which may be of any material and height.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The fair territory between home plate and the outfield boundary is baseball's field of play, though significant events can take place in foul territory, as well.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Protective helmets are also standard equipment for all batters.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] At the beginning of each half-inning, the nine players of the fielding team arrange themselves around the field.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] One of them, the pitcher, stands on the pitcher's mound.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The pitcher begins the pitching delivery with one foot on the rubber, pushing off it to gain velocity when throwing toward home plate.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Another fielding team player, the catcher, squats on the far side of home plate, facing the pitcher.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The rest of the fielding team faces home plate, typically arranged as four infielders—who set up along or within a few yards outside the imaginary lines (basepaths) between first, second, and third base—and three outfielders.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] In the standard arrangement, there is a first baseman positioned several steps to the left of first base, a second baseman to the right of second base, a shortstop to the left of second base, and a third baseman to the right of third base.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The basic outfield positions are left fielder, center fielder, and right fielder.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] With the exception of the catcher, all fielders are required to be in fair territory when the pitch is delivered.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] A neutral umpire sets up behind the catcher.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Other umpires will be distributed around the field as well.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Play starts with a member of the batting team, the batter, standing in either of the two batter's boxes next to home plate, holding a bat.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The batter waits for the pitcher to throw a pitch (the ball) toward home plate, and attempts to hit the ball with the bat.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The catcher catches pitches that the batter does not hit—as a result of either electing not to swing or failing to connect—and returns them to the pitcher.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] A batter who hits the ball into the field of play must drop the bat and begin running toward first base, at which point the player is referred to as a *runner* (or, until the play is over, a *batter-runner*).
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] A batter-runner who reaches first base without being put out is said to be *safe* and is on base.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] A batter-runner may choose to remain at first base or attempt to advance to second base or even beyond—however far the player believes can be reached safely.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] A player who reaches base despite proper play by the fielders has recorded a hit.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] A player who reaches first base safely on a hit is credited with a single.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] If a player makes it to second base safely as a direct result of a hit, it is a double; third base, a triple.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] If the ball is hit in the air within the foul lines over the entire outfield (and outfield fence, if there is one), or if the batter-runner otherwise safely circles all the bases, it is a home run: the batter and any runners on base may all freely circle the bases, each scoring a run.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] This is the most desirable result for the batter.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The ultimate and most desirable result possible for a batter would be to hit a home run while all three bases are occupied or "loaded", thus scoring four runs on a single hit.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] A player who reaches base due to a fielding mistake is not credited with a hit—instead, the responsible fielder is charged with an error.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Any runners already on base may attempt to advance on batted balls that land, or contact the ground, in fair territory, before or after the ball lands.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] A runner on first base *must* attempt to advance if a ball lands in play, as only one runner may occupy a base at any given time; the same applies for other runners if they are on a base that a teammate is forced to advance to.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] If a ball hit into play rolls foul before passing through the infield, it becomes dead and any runners must return to the base they occupied when the play began.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] If the ball is hit in the air and caught before it lands, the batter has flied out and any runners on base may attempt to advance only if they tag up (contact the base they occupied when the play began, as or after the ball is caught).
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Runners may also attempt to advance to the next base while the pitcher is in the process of delivering the ball to home plate; a successful effort is a stolen base.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] A pitch that is not hit into the field of play is called either a strike or a ball.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] A batter against whom three strikes are recorded strikes out.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] A batter against whom four balls are recorded is awarded a base on balls or walk, a free advance to first base.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] While the team at bat is trying to score runs, the team in the field is attempting to record outs.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] In addition to the strikeout and flyout, common ways a member of the batting team may be put out include the ground out, force out, and tag out.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] These occur either when a runner is forced to advance to a base, and a fielder with possession of the ball reaches that base before the runner does, or the runner is touched by the ball, held in a fielder's hand, while not on a base.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] (The batter-runner is always forced to advance to first base, and any other runners must advance to the next base if a teammate is forced to advance to their base.) It is possible to record two outs in the course of the same play.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Three outs in one play, a triple play, is possible, though rare.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Players put out or retired must leave the field, returning to their team's dugout or bench.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] A runner may be stranded on base when a third out is recorded against another player on the team.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Stranded runners do not benefit the team in its next turn at bat as every half-inning begins with the bases empty.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] An individual player's turn batting or plate appearance is complete when the player reaches base, hits a home run, makes an out, or hits a ball that results in the team's third out, even if it is recorded against a teammate.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] On rare occasions, a batter may be at the plate when, without the batter's hitting the ball, a third out is recorded against a teammate—for instance, a runner getting caught stealing (tagged out attempting to steal a base).
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] A batter with this sort of incomplete plate appearance starts off the team's next turn batting; any balls or strikes recorded against the batter the previous inning are erased.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] A runner may circle the bases only once per plate appearance and thus can score at most a single run per batting turn.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Once a player has completed a plate appearance, that player may not bat again until the eight other members of the player's team have all taken their turn at bat in the batting order.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The batting order is set before the game begins, and may not be altered except for substitutions.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Once a player has been removed for a substitute, that player may not reenter the game.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Children's games often have more lenient rules, such as Little League rules, which allow players to be substituted back into the same game.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] If the designated hitter (DH) rule is in effect, each team has a tenth player whose sole responsibility is to bat (and run).
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The DH takes the place of another player—almost invariably the pitcher—in the batting order, but does not field.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Thus, even with the DH, each team still has a batting order of nine players and a fielding arrangement of nine players.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The number of players on a baseball roster, or *squad*, varies by league and by the level of organized play.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] A Major League Baseball (MLB) team has a roster of 26 players with specific roles.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Most baseball leagues worldwide have the DH rule, including MLB, Japan's Pacific League, and Caribbean professional leagues, along with major American amateur organizations.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The Central League in Japan does not have the rule and high-level minor league clubs connected to National League teams are not required to field a DH.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] In leagues that apply the designated hitter rule, a typical team has nine offensive regulars (including the DH), five starting pitchers, seven or eight relievers, a backup catcher, and two or three other reserve players.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The manager, or head coach, oversees the team's major strategic decisions, such as establishing the starting rotation, setting the lineup, or batting order, before each game, and making substitutions during games—in particular, bringing in relief pitchers.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Managers are typically assisted by two or more coaches; they may have specialized responsibilities, such as working with players on hitting, fielding, pitching, or strength and conditioning.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] At most levels of organized play, two coaches are stationed on the field when the team is at bat: the first base coach and third base coach, who occupy designated coaches' boxes, just outside the foul lines.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] These coaches assist in the direction of baserunners, when the ball is in play, and relay tactical signals from the manager to batters and runners, during pauses in play.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] In contrast to many other team sports, baseball managers and coaches generally wear their team's uniforms; coaches must be in uniform to be allowed on the field to confer with players during a game.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Any baseball game involves one or more umpires, who make rulings on the outcome of each play.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] At a minimum, one umpire will stand behind the catcher, to have a good view of the strike zone, and call balls and strikes.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Additional umpires may be stationed near the other bases, thus making it easier to judge plays such as attempted force outs and tag outs.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] In MLB, four umpires are used for each game, one near each base.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] In the playoffs, six umpires are used: one at each base and two in the outfield along the foul lines.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Many of the pre-game and in-game strategic decisions in baseball revolve around a fundamental fact: in general, right-handed batters tend to be more successful against left-handed pitchers and, to an even greater degree, left-handed batters tend to be more successful against right-handed pitchers.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] A manager with several left-handed batters in the regular lineup, who knows the team will be facing a left-handed starting pitcher, may respond by starting one or more of the right-handed backups on the team's roster.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] During the late innings of a game, as relief pitchers and pinch hitters are brought in, the opposing managers will often go back and forth trying to create favorable matchups with their substitutions.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The manager of the fielding team trying to arrange same-handed pitcher-batter matchups and the manager of the batting team trying to arrange opposite-handed matchups.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] With a team that has the lead in the late innings, a manager may remove a starting position player—especially one whose turn at bat is not likely to come up again—for a more skillful fielder (known as a defensive substitution).
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The tactical decision that precedes almost every play in a baseball game involves pitch selection.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] By gripping and then releasing the baseball in a certain manner, and by throwing it at a certain speed, pitchers can cause the baseball to break to either side, or downward, as it approaches the batter, thus creating differing pitches that can be selected.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Among the resulting wide variety of pitches that may be thrown, the four basic types are the fastball, the changeup (or off-speed pitch), and two breaking balls—the curveball and the slider.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Pitchers have different repertoires of pitches they are skillful at throwing.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Conventionally, before each pitch, the catcher signals the pitcher what type of pitch to throw, as well as its general vertical or horizontal location.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] If there is disagreement on the selection, the pitcher may shake off the sign and the catcher will call for a different pitch.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] With a runner on base and taking a lead, the pitcher may attempt a pickoff, a quick throw to a fielder covering the base to keep the runner's lead in check or, optimally, effect a tag out.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Pickoff attempts, however, are subject to rules that severely restrict the pitcher's movements before and during the pickoff attempt.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Violation of any one of these rules could result in the umpire calling a balk against the pitcher, which permits any runners on base to advance one base with impunity.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] If an attempted stolen base is anticipated, the catcher may call for a pitchout, a ball thrown deliberately off the plate, allowing the catcher to catch it while standing and throw quickly to a base.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Facing a batter with a strong tendency to hit to one side of the field, the fielding team may employ a shift, with most or all of the fielders moving to the left or right of their usual positions.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] With a runner on third base, the infielders may play in, moving closer to home plate to improve the odds of throwing out the runner on a ground ball, though a sharply hit grounder is more likely to carry through a drawn-in infield.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Several basic offensive tactics come into play with a runner on first base, including the fundamental choice of whether to attempt a steal of second base.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The hit and run is sometimes employed, with a skillful contact hitter, the runner takes off with the pitch, drawing the shortstop or second baseman over to second base, creating a gap in the infield for the batter to poke the ball through.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The sacrifice bunt, calls for the batter to focus on making soft contact with the ball, so that it rolls a short distance into the infield, allowing the runner to advance into scoring position as the batter is thrown out at first.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] A batter, particularly one who is a fast runner, may also attempt to bunt for a hit.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] A sacrifice bunt employed with a runner on third base, aimed at bringing that runner home, is known as a squeeze play.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] With a runner on third and fewer than two outs, a batter may instead concentrate on hitting a fly ball that, even if it is caught, will be deep enough to allow the runner to tag up and score—a successful batter, in this case, gets credit for a sacrifice fly.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] In order to increase the chance of advancing a batter to first base via a walk, the manager will sometimes signal a batter who is ahead in the count (i.e., has more balls than strikes) to take, or not swing at, the next pitch.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The batter's potential reward of reaching base (via a walk) exceeds the disadvantage if the next pitch is a strike.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Consensus once held that today's baseball is a North American development from the older game rounders, popular among children in Great Britain and Ireland.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] American baseball historian David Block suggests that the game originated in England; recently uncovered historical evidence supports this position.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] According to Block and official MLB historian John Thorn, this earlier version of baseball may have involved hitting the ball with a hand, making it akin to today's punchball.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Block argues that rounders and early baseball were actually regional variants of each other, and that the game's most direct antecedents are the English games of stoolball and "tut-ball".
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The earliest known reference to baseball is in a 1744 British publication, *A Little Pretty Pocket-Book*, by John Newbery.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Block discovered that the first recorded game of "Base Ball" took place in 1749 in Surrey, and featured the Prince of Wales as a player.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] This early form of the game was apparently brought to Canada by English immigrants.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] By the early 1830s, there were reports of a variety of uncodified bat-and-ball games recognizable as early forms of baseball being played around North America.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The first recorded baseball game in North America was played in Beachville, Ontario, Canada, on June 4, 1838.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] In 1845, Alexander Cartwright, a member of New York City's Knickerbocker Club, led the codification of the so-called Knickerbocker Rules, which in turn were based on rules developed in 1837 by William R.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] While there are reports that the New York Knickerbockers played games in 1845, the contest long recognized as the first recorded baseball game in U.S. history took place on June 19, 1846, in Hoboken, New Jersey: the "New York Nine" defeated the Knickerbockers, 23–1, in four innings.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] With the Knickerbocker code as the basis, the rules of modern baseball continued to evolve over the next half-century.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The game then went on to spread throughout the Pacific Rim and the Americas, with Americans backing the sport as a way to spread American values.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] In the mid-1850s, a baseball craze hit the New York metropolitan area, and by 1856, local journals were referring to baseball as the "national pastime" or "national game".
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] A year later, the sport's first governing body, the National Association of Base Ball Players, was formed.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] In 1867, it barred participation by African Americans.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The more formally structured National League was founded in 1876.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Professional Negro leagues formed, but quickly folded.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] In 1887, softball, under the name of indoor baseball or indoor-outdoor, was invented as a winter version of the parent game.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The American League evolved from the minor Western League, which was reorganized under Ban Johnson in 1893.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] It was not until 1901 that the American League was formally established as a major league.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] By 1893, crucial structural changes (like moving the pitching distance to 60 feet, 6 inches) firmly cemented the modern rulebook.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The National Agreement of 1903 formalized relations both between the two major leagues and between them and the National Association of Professional Base Ball Leagues, representing most of the country's minor professional leagues.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The World Series, pitting the two major league champions against each other, was inaugurated that fall.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The Black Sox Scandal of the 1919 World Series led to the formation of the office of the Commissioner of Baseball.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The first commissioner, Kenesaw Mountain Landis, was elected in 1920.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] That year also saw the founding of the Negro National League; the first significant Negro league, it would operate until 1931.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] For part of the 1920s, it was joined by the Eastern Colored League.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Compared with the present, professional baseball in the early 20th century was lower-scoring, and pitchers were more dominant.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] This so-called "dead-ball era" ended in the early 1920s with several changes in rule and circumstance that were advantageous to hitters.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Strict new regulations that governed the ball's size, shape and composition, along with a new rule officially banning the spitball and other pitches that depended on the ball being treated or roughed-up with foreign substances, resulted in a ball that traveled farther when hit.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The rise of the legendary player Babe Ruth, the first great power hitter of the new era, helped permanently alter the nature of the game.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Louis Cardinals general manager Branch Rickey invested in several minor league clubs and developed the first modern farm system.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] A new Negro National League was organized in 1933; four years later, it was joined by the Negro American League.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The first elections to the National Baseball Hall of Fame took place in 1936.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] In 1939, Little League Baseball was founded in Pennsylvania.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Many minor league teams disbanded when World War II led to a player shortage.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Wrigley led the formation of the All-American Girls Professional Baseball League to help keep the game in the public eye.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The first crack in the unwritten agreement barring blacks from white-controlled professional ball occurred in 1945: Jackie Robinson was signed by the National League's Brooklyn Dodgers and began playing for their minor league team in Montreal.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] In 1947, Robinson broke the major leagues' color barrier when he debuted with the Dodgers.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Latin-American players, largely overlooked before, also started entering the majors in greater numbers.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] In 1951, two Chicago White Sox, Venezuelan-born Chico Carrasquel and black Cuban-born Minnie Miñoso, became the first Hispanic All-Stars.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Integration proceeded slowly: by 1953, only six of the 16 major league teams had a black player on the roster.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] In 1975, the union's power—and players' salaries—began to increase greatly when the reserve clause was effectively struck down, leading to the free agency system.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Significant work stoppages occurred in 1981 and 1994, the latter forcing the cancellation of the World Series for the first time in 90 years.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Attendance had been growing steadily since the mid-1970s and in 1994, before the stoppage, the majors were setting their all-time record for per-game attendance.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] After play resumed in 1995, non-division-winning wild card teams became a permanent fixture of the post-season.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Regular-season interleague play was introduced in 1997 and the second-highest attendance mark for a full season was set.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] In 2000, the National and American Leagues were dissolved as legal entities.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] While their identities were maintained for scheduling purposes (and the designated hitter distinction), the regulations and other functions—such as player discipline and umpire supervision—they had administered separately were consolidated under the rubric of MLB.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] In 2001, Barry Bonds established the current record of 73 home runs in a single season.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] In 2007, Bonds became MLB's all-time home run leader, surpassing Hank Aaron, as total major league and minor league attendance both reached all-time highs.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Despite having been called "America's national pastime", baseball is well-established in several other countries.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] As early as 1877, a professional league, the International Association, featured teams from both Canada and the United States.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] While baseball is widely played in Canada and many minor league teams have been based in the country, the American major leagues did not include a Canadian club until 1969, when the Montreal Expos joined the National League as an expansion team.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] In 1977, the expansion Toronto Blue Jays joined the American League.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] In 1847, American soldiers played what may have been the first baseball game in Mexico at Parque Los Berros in Xalapa, Veracruz.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The first formal baseball league outside of the United States and Canada was founded in 1878 in Cuba, which maintains a rich baseball tradition.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The English football club, Aston Villa, were the first British baseball champions winning the 1890 National League of Baseball of Great Britain.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The 2025 National Champions were the London Mets.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The Dominican Republic held its first islandwide championship tournament in 1912.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Professional baseball tournaments and leagues began to form in other countries between the world wars, including the Netherlands (formed in 1922), Australia (1934), Japan (1936), Mexico (1937), and Puerto Rico (1938).
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The Japanese major leagues have long been considered the highest quality professional circuits outside of the United States.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] After World War II, professional leagues were founded in many Latin American countries, most prominently Venezuela (1946) and the Dominican Republic (1955).
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Since the early 1970s, the annual Caribbean Series has matched the championship clubs from the four leading Latin American winter leagues: the Dominican Professional Baseball League, Mexican Pacific League, Puerto Rican Professional Baseball League, and Venezuelan Professional Baseball League.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] In Asia, South Korea (1982), Taiwan (1990) and China (2003) all have professional leagues.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Other European countries have seen professional leagues; the most successful, other than the Dutch league, is the Italian league, founded in 1948.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] In 2004, Australia won a surprise silver medal at the Olympic Games.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The Confédération Européene de Baseball (European Baseball Confederation), founded in 1953, organizes a number of competitions between clubs from different countries.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Women's baseball is played on an organized amateur basis in numerous countries.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] After being admitted to the Olympics as a medal sport beginning with the 1992 Games, baseball was dropped from the 2012 Summer Olympic Games at the 2005 International Olympic Committee meeting.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] While the sport's lack of a following in much of the world was a factor, more important was MLB's reluctance to allow its players to participate during the major league season.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] MLB initiated the World Baseball Classic, scheduled to precede its season, partly as a replacement, high-profile international tournament.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The inaugural Classic, held in March 2006, was the first tournament involving national teams to feature a significant number of MLB participants.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The Baseball World Cup was discontinued after its 2011 edition in favor of an expanded World Baseball Classic.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Baseball has certain attributes that set it apart from the other popular team sports in the countries where it has a following.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] All of these sports use a clock, play is less individual, and the variation between playing fields is not as substantial or important.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The comparison between cricket and baseball demonstrates that many of baseball's distinctive elements are shared in various ways with similar sports.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] In clock-limited sports, games often end with a team that holds the lead killing the clock rather than competing aggressively against the opposing team.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] In contrast, baseball has no clock, thus a team cannot win without getting the last batter out and rallies are not constrained by time.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] At almost any turn in any baseball game, the most advantageous strategy is some form of aggressive strategy.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] While nine innings has been the standard since the beginning of professional baseball, the duration of the average major league game has increased steadily through the years.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] At the turn of the 20th century, games typically took an hour and a half to play.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] In the 1920s, they averaged just less than two hours, which eventually ballooned to 2:38 in 1960.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] By 1997, the average American League game lasted 2:57 (National League games were about 10 minutes shorter—pitchers at the plate making for quicker outs than designated hitters).
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] In 2004, Major League Baseball declared that its goal was an average game of 2:45.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] By 2014, though, the average MLB game took over three hours to complete.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The lengthening of games is attributed to longer breaks between half-innings for television commercials, increased offense, more pitching changes, and a slower pace of play, with pitchers taking more time between each delivery, and batters stepping out of the box more frequently.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Other leagues have experienced similar issues.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] In 2008, Nippon Professional Baseball took steps aimed at shortening games by 12 minutes from the preceding decade's average of 3:18.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] In 2016, the average nine-inning playoff game in Major League baseball was 3 hours and 35 minutes.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] This was up 10 minutes from 2015 and 21 minutes from 2014.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] In response to the lengthening of the game, MLB decided from the 2023 season onward to institute a pitch clock rule to penalize batters and pitchers who take too much time between pitches; this had the effect of shortening 2023 regular season games by 24 minutes on average.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Although baseball is a team sport, individual players are often placed under scrutiny and pressure.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] While rewarding, it has sometimes been described as "ruthless" due to the pressure on the individual player.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] In 1915, a baseball instructional manual pointed out that every single pitch, of which there are often more than two hundred in a game, involves an individual, one-on-one contest: "the pitcher and the batter in a battle of wits".
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Pitcher, batter, and fielder all act essentially independent of each other.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] While coaching staffs can signal pitcher or batter to pursue certain tactics, the execution of the play itself is a series of solitary acts.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] If the batter hits a line drive, the outfielder is solely responsible for deciding to try to catch it or play it on the bounce and for succeeding or failing.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The statistical precision of baseball is both facilitated by this isolation and reinforces it.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] There is no statistical equivalent in cricket for the fielding error and thus less emphasis on personal responsibility in this area of play.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Unlike those of most sports, baseball playing fields can vary significantly in size and shape.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Major league teams often skirt even this rule.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] For example, at Daikin Park, which became the home of the Houston Astros in 2000, the Crawford Boxes in left field are only 315 feet (96 m) from home plate.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] There are no rules at all that address the height of fences or other structures at the edge of the outfield.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The most famously idiosyncratic outfield boundary is the left-field wall at Boston's Fenway Park, in use since 1912: the Green Monster is 310 feet (94 m) from home plate down the line and 37 feet (11 m) tall.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Similarly, there are no regulations at all concerning the dimensions of foul territory.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Thus a foul fly ball may be entirely out of play in a park with little space between the foul lines and the stands, but a foulout in a park with more expansive foul ground.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] A fence in foul territory that is close to the outfield line will tend to direct balls that strike it back toward the fielders, while one that is farther away may actually prompt more collisions, as outfielders run full speed to field balls deep in the corner.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] These variations can make the difference between a double and a triple or inside-the-park home run.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The surface of the field is also unregulated.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] While the adjacent image shows a traditional field surfacing arrangement (and the one used by virtually all MLB teams with naturally surfaced fields), teams are free to decide what areas will be grassed or bare.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Some fields—including several in MLB—use artificial turf.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Surface variations can have a significant effect on how ground balls behave and are fielded as well as on baserunning.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Similarly, the presence of a roof (seven major league teams play in stadiums with permanent or retractable roofs) can greatly affect how fly balls are played.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] While football and soccer players deal with similar variations of field surface and stadium covering, the size and shape of their fields are much more standardized.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The area out-of-bounds on a football or soccer field does not affect play the way foul territory in baseball does, so variations in that regard are largely insignificant.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] These physical variations create a distinctive set of playing conditions at each ballpark.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Other local factors, such as altitude and climate, can also significantly affect play.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] A given stadium may acquire a reputation as a pitcher's park or a hitter's park, if one or the other discipline notably benefits from its unique mix of elements.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The most exceptional park in this regard is Coors Field, home of the Colorado Rockies.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Its high altitude—5,282 feet (1,610 m) above sea level—is partly responsible for giving it the strongest hitter's park effect in the major leagues due to the low air pressure.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] Wrigley Field, home of the Chicago Cubs, is known for its fickle disposition: a pitcher's park when the strong winds off Lake Michigan are blowing in, it becomes more of a hitter's park when they are blowing out.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] The absence of a standardized field affects not only how particular games play out, but the nature of team rosters and players' statistical records.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] For example, hitting a fly ball 330 feet (100 m) into right field might result in an easy catch on the warning track at one park, and a home run at another.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] A team that plays in a park with a relatively short right field, such as the New York Yankees, will tend to stock its roster with left-handed pull hitters, who can best exploit it.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p01] On the individual level, a player who spends most of his career with a team that plays in a hitter's park will gain an advantage in batting statistics over time—even more so if his talents are especially suited to the park.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Organized baseball lends itself to statistics to a greater degree than many other sports.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Each play is discrete and has a relatively small number of possible outcomes.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] The Official Baseball Rules administered by MLB require the official scorer to categorize each baseball play unambiguously.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] The rules provide detailed criteria to promote consistency.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] The score report is the official basis for both the box score of the game and the relevant statistical records.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] General managers, managers, and baseball scouts use statistics to evaluate players and make strategic decisions.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Certain traditional statistics are familiar to most baseball fans.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Among the many other statistics that are kept are those collectively known as *situational statistics*.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] For example, statistics can indicate which specific pitchers a certain batter performs best against.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] If a given situation statistically favors a certain batter, the manager of the fielding team may be more likely to change pitchers or have the pitcher intentionally walk the batter in order to face one who is less likely to succeed.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Sabermetrics is the field of baseball statistical study and the development of new statistics and analytical tools.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Such new statistics are also called sabermetrics.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] The term was coined around 1980 by one of the field's leading proponents, Bill James, and derives from the Society for American Baseball Research (SABR).
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Writing in 1919, philosopher Morris Raphael Cohen described baseball as the national religion of the US.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] In the words of sports columnist Jayson Stark, baseball has long been "a unique paragon of American culture"—a status he sees as devastated by the steroid abuse scandal.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] American influence in the Western Hemisphere has meant that baseball grew significantly in the region.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] A century later, the situation was very different.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] With the rise in popularity of other team sports with much higher average ticket prices—football, basketball, and hockey—professional baseball had become among the most popular blue-collar-oriented American spectator sports.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Overall, baseball has a large following in the United States; a 2006 poll found that nearly half of Americans are fans.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] This led to baseball being granted the title of "America's favorite pastime" by many American baseball fans.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] As historians and scholars now speculate, baseball is a metaphor of the American way of life In the late 1900s and early 2000s, baseball's position compared to football in the United States moved in contradictory directions.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] In 2008, MLB set a revenue record of $6.5 billion, matching the NFL's revenue for the first time in decades.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] A new MLB revenue record of more than $10 billion was set in 2017.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] On the other hand, the percentage of American sports fans polled who named baseball as their favorite sport was 9%, compared to pro football at 37%.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] In 1985, the respective figures were pro football 24%, baseball 23%.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Because there are so many more major league games played, there is no comparison in overall attendance.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] In 2008, total attendance at major league games was the second-highest in history: 78.6 million, 0.7% off the record set the previous year.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] The following year, amid the U.S. recession, attendance fell by 6.6% to 73.4 million.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Eight years later, it dropped under 73 million.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Attendance at games held under the Minor League Baseball umbrella set a record in 2008, with 43.3 million.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] While MLB games have not drawn the same national TV viewership as football games, MLB games are dominant in teams' local markets and regularly lead all programs in primetime in their markets during the summer.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] After multiple years of declines since 2017, baseball attendance has grown slightly in recent years.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] In 2024, attendance was 71.3 million, the highest since 2017.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Baseball is very popular in Venezuela; in 2011, 95% of people surveyed claimed it to be the national sport.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] In Nicaragua and Panama, baseball is also considered the national sport.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] While soccer is still more popular, baseball is a fast-growing sport in Mexico.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] In 2024, top Mexican League baseball teams outdraw some Liga MX teams in attendance.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Baseball also is somewhat popular in Colombia, though secondary to soccer, especially in coastal areas such as Barranquilla and Cartagena which are near the Caribbean.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] In recent years, baseball has grown in popularity in Colombia, especially in the capital of Bogotá, due an increase of Venezuelan immigrants.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] In Brazil, baseball fan popularity has grown in the last few years, thanks to MLB broadcasts in Brazilian ESPN and the historic silver medal in 2023 Pan-American games.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] However, it still lags behind basketball and American football in the list of most played sports in Brazil.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Baseball has also grown in popularity in Argentina and Peru in recent years due to Venezuelan immigrants.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Costa Rica has also seen a growth in the popularity of baseball.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Since 1987, baseballs have exclusively been made in the Costa Rican town of Turrialba.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] In recent years, Major leaguer Mauricio Dubón has made efforts to increase support for the sport in the country.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] The sport's overall popularity in Latin America has assisted in integrating Latin American migrants to the United States.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Since the early 1980s, the Dominican Republic, in particular the city of San Pedro de Macorís, has been the major leagues' primary source of foreign talent.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] In 2017, 83 of the 868 players on MLB Opening Day rosters (and disabled lists) were from the country.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Among other Caribbean countries and territories, a combined 97 MLB players were born in Venezuela, Cuba, and Puerto Rico.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Hall-of-Famer Roberto Clemente remains one of the greatest national heroes in Puerto Rico's history.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] While baseball has long been the island's primary athletic pastime, its once well-attended professional winter league has declined in popularity since 1990, when young Puerto Rican players began to be included in the major leagues' annual first-year player draft.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] In Cuba, where baseball is by every reckoning the national sport, the national team overshadows the city and provincial teams that play in the top-level domestic leagues.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Baseball is also one of the most popular sports of Aruba and Curaçao, and a growing sport in The Bahamas and the US Virgin Islands.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] In East Asia, baseball is among the most popular sports in Japan, Taiwan and South Korea.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] In Japan, where baseball is inarguably the leading spectator team sport, combined revenue for the twelve teams in Nippon Professional Baseball (NPB), the body that oversees both the Central and Pacific Leagues, was estimated at $1 billion in 2007.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Total NPB attendance for the year was approximately 20 million.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] While in the preceding two decades, MLB attendance grew by 50 percent and revenue nearly tripled, the comparable NPB figures were stagnant.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] There are concerns that MLB's growing interest in acquiring star Japanese players will hurt the game in their home country.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Revenue figures are not released for the country's amateur system.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Similarly, according to one official pronouncement, the sport's governing authority "has never taken into account attendance ... because its greatest interest has always been the development of athletes".
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] In Taiwan, baseball is one of the most widely spectated sports, in TV and person.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Baseball has grown significantly in China in recent years, with MLB estimating in 2019 that there are 21 million active fans in the country.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Baseball was considered a national pastime in the Philippines in the 1960s and 70s, but the sport has since declined in popularity.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Since 2005, there have been efforts to revitalize the sport in the country.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Baseball saw a surge in popularity in Thailand following the countries' silver medal in baseball in the 2025 SEA Games, which were hosted in Thailand.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Baseball is generally a niche sport in Europe.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] However, baseball is somewhat popular in the Netherlands, where it is known as *honkbal*, thanks to influence from the United States after World War II and the Kingdoms control over Aruba and Curaçao where it is the most popular sport.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Baseball is also somewhat popular in portions of Italy, especially in the town of Nettuno, due to influence from American soldiers after World War II.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Baseball has grown in recent years in the Czech Republic, due in part to the Czech teams' success in the 2023 World Baseball Classic.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Baseball is one of the most popular sports in Palau and Guam.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] In Australia, baseball is a niche sport but the country does have a professional league.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Because the league is played in winter for the western hemisphere, it attracts American and Korean professional players looking to play winter league baseball.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] In 2026, there were more than 30 Australians playing college baseball in the United States compared to six in 2020.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] The Dodgers operate a large baseball academy in Mpigi, Uganda, and there are also baseball programs in Luwero, Uganda.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] There is also a Africa Baseball Academy in Nairobi, Nigeria.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Baseball was popular in South Africa prior to World War 2 but popularity has since waned.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] There are still teams and attempts to raise the popularity of baseball in the country, including the introduction of Baseball5.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] There is a growing baseball program in South Sudan, which has resulted in professional contracts.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] The Japan-Africa Baseball & Softball Foundation has created Koshien high school baseball tournaments in Tanzania, Ghana and Kenya, which Tanzania being the most successful.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] There are further plans for similar tournaments in Nigeria, South Sudan, Benin, Cameroon and Zambia.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] As of 2024, Little League Baseball oversees leagues with 2 million participants in more than 80 countries.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] The number of players has fallen since the 1990s, when 3 million children took part in Little League Baseball annually.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Babe Ruth League teams have over 1 million participants.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] According to the president of the International Baseball Federation in 2009, between 300,000 and 500,000 women and girls play baseball around the world, including Little League and the introductory game of Tee Ball.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] A varsity baseball team is an established part of physical education departments at most high schools and colleges in the United States.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] In 2015, nearly half a million high schoolers and over 34,000 collegians played on their schools' baseball teams.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] By early in the 20th century, intercollegiate baseball was Japan's leading sport.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Today, high school baseball in particular is immensely popular there.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] The final rounds of the two annual tournaments—the National High School Baseball Invitational Tournament in the spring, and the even more important National High School Baseball Championship in the summer—are broadcast around the country.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] The tournaments are known, respectively, as Spring Koshien and Summer Koshien after the 55,000-capacity stadium where they are played.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] In Cuba, baseball is a mandatory part of the state system of physical education, which begins at age six.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Talented children as young as seven are sent to special district schools for more intensive training—the first step on a ladder whose acme is the national baseball team.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Baseball has had a broad impact on popular culture, both in the United States and elsewhere.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Dozens of English-language idioms have been derived from baseball; in particular, the game is the source of a number of widely used sexual euphemisms.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] The first networked radio broadcasts in North America were of the 1922 World Series: famed sportswriter Grantland Rice announced play-by-play from New York City's Polo Grounds on WJZ–Newark, New Jersey, which was connected by wire to WGY–Schenectady, New York, and WBZ–Springfield, Massachusetts.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] The baseball cap has become a ubiquitous fashion item not only in the United States and Japan, but also in countries where the sport itself is not particularly popular, such as the United Kingdom.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Baseball has inspired many works of art and entertainment.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] There have been many baseball movies, including the Academy Award–winning *The Pride of the Yankees* (1942) and the Oscar nominees *The Natural* (1984) and *Field of Dreams* (1989).
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] The American Film Institute's selection of the ten best sports movies includes *The Pride of the Yankees* at number 3 and *Bull Durham* (1988) at number 5.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Baseball has provided thematic material for hits on both stage—the Adler–Ross musical *Damn Yankees*—and record—George J.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Gaskin's "Slide, Kelly, Slide", Simon and Garfunkel's "Mrs.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Robinson", and John Fogerty's "Centerfield".
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] The baseball-inspired comedic sketch "Who's on First?", popularized by Abbott and Costello in 1938, quickly became famous; six decades later, *Time* named it the best comedy routine of the 20th century.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Literary works connected to the game include the short fiction of Ring Lardner and novels such as Bernard Malamud's *The Natural* (the source for the movie), Robert Coover's *The Universal Baseball Association, Inc., J.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Henry Waugh, Prop.*, John Grisham's Calico Joe and W.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Kinsella's *Shoeless Joe* (the source for *Field of Dreams*).
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Baseball's literary canon also includes the beat reportage of Damon Runyon; the columns of Grantland Rice, Red Smith, Dick Young, and Peter Gammons; and the essays of Roger Angell.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Among the celebrated nonfiction books in the field are Lawrence S.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Ritter's *The Glory of Their Times*, Roger Kahn's *The Boys of Summer*, and Michael Lewis's *Moneyball*.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] The 1970 publication of major league pitcher Jim Bouton's tell-all chronicle *Ball Four* is considered a turning point in the reporting of professional sports.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Baseball has also inspired the creation of new cultural forms.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Baseball cards were introduced in the late 19th century as trade cards.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] A typical example featured an image of a baseball player on one side and advertising for a business on the other.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] In the early 1900s they were produced widely as promotional items by tobacco and confectionery companies.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] The 1930s saw the popularization of the modern style of baseball card, with a player photograph accompanied on the rear by statistics and biographical data.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Baseball cards—many of which are now prized collectibles—are the source of the much broader trading card industry, involving similar products for different sports and non-sports-related fields.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Modern fantasy sports began in 1980 with the invention of Rotisserie League Baseball by New York writer Daniel Okrent and several friends.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Participants in a Rotisserie league draft notional teams from the list of active MLB players and play out an entire imaginary season with game outcomes based on the players' latest real-world statistics.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Rotisserie-style play quickly became a phenomenon.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Now known more generically as fantasy baseball, it has inspired similar games based on an array of different sports.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] The field boomed with increasing Internet access and new fantasy sports-related websites.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] By 2008, 29.9 million people in the United States and Canada were playing fantasy sports, spending $800 million on the hobby.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] The burgeoning popularity of fantasy baseball is also credited with the increasing attention paid to sabermetrics—first among fans, only later among baseball professionals.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Informal variations of baseball have popped up over time, with games like corkball reflecting local traditions and allowing the game to be played in diverse environments.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Two variations of baseball, softball and Baseball5, are internationally governed alongside baseball by the World Baseball Softball Confederation.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] American professional baseball teams toured Britain in 1874 and 1889, and had a great effect on similar sports in Britain.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] In Wales and Merseyside, a strong community game had already developed with skills and plays more in keeping with the American game and the Welsh began to informally adopt the name "baseball" (Pêl Fas), to reflect the American style.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] By the 1890s, calls were made to follow the success of other working class sports (like Rugby in Wales and Soccer in Merseyside) and adopt a distinct set of rules and bureaucracy.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] During the 1892 season rules for the game of "baseball" were agreed and the game was officially codified.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] Finnish baseball, also known as pesäpallo, is a combination of traditional ball-batting team games and North American baseball, invented by Lauri "Tahko" Pihkala in the 1920s.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] The basic idea of pesäpallo is similar to that of baseball: the offense tries to score by hitting the ball successfully and running through the bases, while the defense tries to put the batter and runners out.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] One of the most important differences between pesäpallo and baseball is that the ball is pitched vertically, which makes hitting the ball, as well as controlling the power and direction of the hit, much easier.
[src:first-baseman/baseball-p02] This gives the offensive game more variety, speed, and tactical aspects compared to baseball.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] A **first baseman**, abbreviated **1B**, is the player on a baseball or softball team who fields the area nearest first base, the first of four bases a baserunner must touch in succession to score a run.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] The first baseman is responsible for the majority of plays made at that base.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] Also called **first sacker** or **cornerman**, the first baseman is ideally a tall player who throws left-handed and possesses good flexibility and quick reflexes.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] Flexibility is needed because the first baseman receives throws from the other infielders, the catcher and the pitcher after they have fielded ground balls.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] In order for the runner to be called out, the first baseman must be able to *stretch* towards the throw and catch it before the runner reaches first base.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] First base is often referred to as "the other hot corner"—the "hot corner" being third base—and therefore, like the third baseman, he must have quick reflexes to field the hardest hit balls down the foul line, mainly by left-handed pull hitters and right-handed hitters hitting to the opposite field.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] Good defensive first basemen, according to baseball writer and historian Bill James, are capable of playing off first base so that they can field ground balls hit to the fair side of first base.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] The first baseman then relies upon the pitcher to cover first base to receive the ball to complete the out.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] Indications of a good defensive first baseman include a large number of assists and a low number of throwing errors by other infielders.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] The nature of play at first base often requires first basemen to stay close to the bag to hold runners or to reach the bag before the batter.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] First basemen are not typically expected to have the range required of a third baseman, shortstop, second baseman or an outfielder.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] As a result, first base is not usually perceived to be as physically demanding as other positions.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] However, it can also be a very hard position to play; a large amount of concentration and timing is required.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] Though many play at first base their entire career, occasionally veteran players move to first base to extend their careers or to accommodate other recently acquired players.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] Facing a possible trade or a considerable reduction in playing time, a player may opt to move to first base instead.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] Catchers and corner outfielders sometimes move to first base due to deteriorating health or if their fielding abilities at their original position are detrimental to the team.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] When first base is not occupied by a baserunner, the first baseman usually stands behind first base and off the foul line.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] The distance he plays from the base and foul line is dependent on the current hitter and any runners on base.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] The exact position may also depend on the first baseman's experience, preference, and fielding ability.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] For a known right-handed pull hitter, the first baseman might position himself further towards the second baseman's normal fielding position.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] For a known left-handed pull hitter, the first baseman will position himself closer to the foul line to stop a ball hit down the line.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] To protect against a bunt on the first base side of the infield, the first baseman will position himself in front of the base and move towards the hitter as the pitch is thrown.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] As soon as the pitcher commits to throwing towards home plate, the first baseman will charge towards the hitter to field the bunt.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] During these plays, it is the responsibility of the second baseman to cover first base.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] With a base runner present at first base, the first baseman stands with their right foot touching the base to prepare for a pickoff attempt.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] Once the pitcher commits to throwing towards home plate, the first baseman comes off the bag in front of the runner and gets in a fielding position.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] If the bases are loaded, or if the runner on first base is not a base stealing threat, the first baseman will position himself behind the runner and appropriate for the current batter.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] When waiting for a throw from another player, the first baseman stands with their off-glove foot touching the base, then stretches toward the throw.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] This stretch decreases the amount of time it takes the throw to get to first and encourages the umpire to call close plays in favor of the fielding team.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] Veteran first basemen are known to pull off the bag early on close plays to convince the umpire that the ball reached their glove before the runner reached first base.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] The first baseman also has the responsibility of cutting off throws from any of the three outfield positions on their way to home plate.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] Though highly situational, the first baseman usually only receives throws from the center or right fielder.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] The *first baseman* is usually at the end of a double play, though he can be at the beginning and end of a double play.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] Unusual double plays involving the first baseman include the 3–6–3, 3–4–3, 3–2–3, or a 3–6–1 double play.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] In a 3–6–3 or 3–4–3 double play, the first baseman fields the ball, throws to second, where the shortstop (6) or second baseman (4) catches the ball to make the first out and then throws back to the first baseman who reaches first base in time to tag first base before the batter reaches first base.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] For a 3–2–3 double play, the bases must be loaded for the force-out at home plate or the catcher must tag the runner coming from third base out.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] With a force-out at home plate, the first baseman fields the ball, throws to the catcher, the catcher steps on home plate for the first out, then he throws it back to the first baseman to complete the double play.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] The 3–2–3 double play with a tag out at home plate is usually not attempted because of the possibility of the catcher not being able to tag the runner and/or block the plate.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] If the runner at third base is known as a good or fast baserunner, the first basemen will make considerable effort to make sure the third base runner does not advance to home plate for a run by "looking" him back to third base.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] The primary goal of the first baseman in this instance is to ensure the runner does not advance and that the team records at least one out, especially in a close game.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] A 3–6–1 double play is almost like a 3–6–3 or a 3–4–3 double play, but the first baseman is usually playing deep in the infield.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] Here, the first baseman throws the ball to the shortstop covering second, but the pitcher then has the responsibility of covering first base to receive the throw from the shortstop.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] A first baseman can theoretically also make an unassisted double play.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] The first is by catching a line drive and returning to first base to tag the base before a baserunner can return.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] This is rare because the first baseman is usually slower than most baserunners who generally return to their bases on line drives near any fielder.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] The second is by getting an infield hit to the right when there is a runner on first, tagging the runner and returning to the first base in time to get the man running towards him.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] A left-handed throwing non-pitcher is often converted to or begins their career playing at first base.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] A left-handed throwing baseball player who is not particularly fast or has a weak arm (and therefore not well suited for playing in the outfield) will usually be relegated to playing first base.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] This is because the only other positions available to the player (catcher, third base, shortstop or second base) are overwhelmingly held by right-handed throwing players, who can make quicker throws to first base (or, in the case of catchers, third base).
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] The same advantages of being a right-handed throwing catcher, third basemen, shortstop or second basemen apply to the left-handed first baseman.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] These advantages surface in plays where the player is required to throw to another infielder after fielding a batted ball.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] In these instances, a right-hander will be required to turn more towards their target before throwing whereas a left-hander will usually already be positioned to make a throw.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] In addition, a majority of plays only require the first baseman to receive a throw, not to field or throw himself.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] This is attributed to the overall majority of baseball players batting right-handed, and therefore, a majority of batted balls are hit to the left side of the infield and fielded by the third baseman or shortstop.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] The first baseman's mitt is similar to a catcher's mitt in that it has extra padding and has no individual fingers.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] (In shape, it is closer to a mitten than a glove.) It is much larger than the other infielders' gloves; it is wide, very deep, and it is crescent-shaped at its edges, allowing the first-baseman to use the mitt like a scoop in catching errant throws from other players on the infield.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] Since many throws to first base are made in great haste, the first baseman must be prepared to catch balls that are either high or low, as well as balls thrown quite a distance to either side, all while maintaining contact with the base (using one foot or the other).
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] This requires a fair amount of agility and physical coordination.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] Among the most difficult plays a first baseman is normally required to make are the "short hop" and the "tag play", both of which are far easier to execute when the fielder is wearing the first-baseman's mitt rather than another type of glove.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] Every ground ball hit to an infielder becomes a race between the batter-runner and the team in the field; the fielder must catch the batted ball and throw it to first before the batter can reach the base.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] Consequently, part of the first baseman's job is to step toward the incoming ball and stretch their body so that their catching hand makes contact with it as soon as physically possible.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] Compared to catching the ball while standing passively on the base, this shaves a fraction of a second from the time the runner has to reach base.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] When it is thrown too low and bounces before reaching the first baseman, catching the ball is difficult, especially while he is in a "stretch position".
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] A throw caught shortly after its bounce, that is, while the baseball's path, rebounding from the turf, is sharply *upward*, is called a "short hop".
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] This technique also minimizes the amount of time required to make the putout.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] The second-most-difficult play for a first baseman is the "tag play".
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] Whenever an infielder's throw is so far off the mark that the first baseman must abandon their base to catch it, the first baseman is left with only two options.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] To put the runner out, he must either lunge back to the base before the runner reaches it, *or* he must tag the runner before the runner reaches the base.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] A tag involves touching the runner with the ball (or with the gloved hand holding the ball) before the runner reaches the base.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] At first base, the typical tag play occurs when the infielder's throw is *high and to the left* of the first baseman, causing him to jump and stretch their long mitt to catch the ball before it sails into the dugout or the grandstand.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] The tag is made, after the catch, by swiping the mitt downward, toward the in-coming runner's head or shoulder, often in one fluid motion that is integrated with the act of catching the ball.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] Performed properly, the tag play can be spectacular to see.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] First basemen are generally not regarded as the most defensively skilled players on a Major League team.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] Someone who has the agility, throwing arm, and raw speed to play another fielding position usually plays somewhere other than first base.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] Additionally, strong-hitting catchers may be put at first base in some games, allowing them to remain in the lineup while reducing the physical demands associated with catching regularly.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] In amateur baseball, left-handed players are frequently assigned to first base, as their throwing orientation limits their suitability for other infield positions, and it also has fewer demands on range and arm strength than other fielding positions like outfield.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] According to Bill James, aside from pitchers and catchers, the most difficult defensive position to play is shortstop, followed by second base, center field, third base, left or right field (depending upon the ballpark), and finally first base as the easiest position.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] Anyone who can play another position on the field can play first base.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] Lou Gehrig is an example of a player who played first base because he was not as strong a fielder as hitter.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] At or near the ends of their careers, good hitters are often moved to first base as their speed and throwing arms deteriorate, a more talented position player was acquired, or their teams become concerned with the likelihood of injury.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] In 2023, Philadelphia Phillies all-star Bryce Harper moved from outfield to first base after undergoing Tommy John surgery; this enabled Harper to return to the field quicker than expected while also lessening the stress of throwing with his surgically repaired right arm.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] Only rarely does a player begin his major-league career at first base and go elsewhere, as with Jackie Robinson, a natural second baseman who was played at first base in his rookie season so that he would avoid the risk of malicious slides at second base.
[src:first-baseman/first-baseman] Hank Greenberg, a natural first baseman for the Detroit Tigers, moved to left field in his 11th major league season (1940) after his team acquired Rudy York, another slugging first baseman who was ill-suited to play anywhere else.
